$f(1)=1$

(Explanation: We are given that the curve $x^2+y^3-2xy=0$ passes through
the point $(1,1)$. Near this point, the curve is the graph of a
function, $y=f(x)$. When $x=1$, $y=f(x)=1$.)

$f'(1)$ is the same thing as $\frac{dy}{dx}$ evaluated at the point
$(x,y)=(1,1)$. In order to find this, we use implicit differentiate the
equation $x^2+y^3-2xy=0$ with respect to $x$.

\begin{align*}
2x+3y^2 \frac{dy}{dx}-2y-2x\frac{dy}{dx}=0 \end{align*}

In order to solve for $\frac{dy}{dx}$, we first factorize,

\begin{align*}
2x-2y+(3y^2-2x) \frac{dy}{dx}=0.\end{align*}

Then subtract $2x-2y$ from both sides and divide by $(3y^2-2x)$ to
obtain

\begin{align*}
 \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{2y-2x}{3y^2-2x}.\end{align*}

When $x=y=1,$

\begin{align*}
 \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{2(1)-2(1)}{3(1)^2-2(1)}=0.\end{align*}

Hence, $\displaystyle f'(1)=0$.
